  "game:craftinginfo-gemcutting-title": "CAN Jewelry: Gemcutting",
  "game:craftinginfo-gemcutting-text": "<strong>Gem cutting</strong><br>  Mod adds various gems to the game that can be encrusted into tools and armor to obtain useful bonuses. Stones have different types effects and power, depending on their processing. <br><br>You can find rough gems by breaking stones/ore blocks or by panning ore chunks(in forged iron/steel <a href=\"handbook://block-canjewelry:canpan-iron\">pan</a>).<br><br>  To use stones you'll need to process them at least on <a href=\"handbook://block-canjewelry:cangemcuttingtable-{{ \\\"metal\\\": \\\"tinbronze\\\", \\\"stone\\\": \\\"andesite\\\" }}\">gem cutting table</a> with <a href=\"handbook://item-canjewelry:cangemchisel-copper\">gem cutting chisel</a>.(Gem cutting table differencies are just decorative and won't affect result gem bonuses.)<br><br>By placeing rough gem on the table you'll see list of cuttings available:<br><br>  - Baguette - gives an additional bonus, but with a lower value than the main one(for example you can have walkspeed on you diamond gem and mining Speed Mul as secondary bonus if you selected this cutting) <br> - Pear - in comparison with gems with other cuttings also without any processing on jewel grinder will have higher bonus(but will lack some if both are fully proccessed on jewel grinder). No secondary bonuses.<br><br> - Round - after full processing the main bonus will have a higher value than Baguette one<br><br> After gem cutting table you'll get cut gem with buff type(s) value(s) on it. To increase it's power you can also process it on jewel grinder. This block requires mechanical power and grindlayers. When grinder is connected and grindlayer is placed(CTRL + Right click)you can process cut gem you have, firstly with rough layer and with fine after that. <br><br> When you have your cut gem ready you can encrust it into tools/armor using Jeweler's table.<br>Besides table you'd need forge sockets. There are three tiers of them:<br><br>- bronze - 1<br>- iron - 2 <br>- steel - 3<br>To see which socket can be placed on your items you need to place them into Jeweler's table:<br>- green - 1 tier<br>- blue - 2 tier<br>- purple - 3 tier<br><br>Gems are divided into tiers as well:<br>- small - can be placed in any socket<br>- medium - in 2. or 3. tier socket<br>- great - only in 3. tier<br><br>Apart from gems there are some craftable items which mod adds you can wear: <br> armbands, coronets, rotten king masks, tiaras,necklaces, monocles, horus eyes. <br>Some of their parts are forged - straps, plates, coronets. Wires can be produced using hammer or on wiredrawing table with higher output",

    "game:craftinginfo-panning_gems-title": "CAN Jewelry: Panning for gems",
    "game:craftinginfo-panning_gems-text": "   Iron/steel pans can be used for obtaining gems from ore chunks of different types. Same as for wooden pan you'd need to stand in water but to start panning you need to place ore chunk in you inventory, in a next right slot. By default it'll take 8 ore chunks per one cycle.<br><br> <strong>Suevite:</strong> all sizes of diamonds (50% small, 30% medium, 20% great)<br><br>All other ores drop depeneds on quality - bountiful/rich will have higher chance than medium or poor but also will have a chace to drop great gems, poor only small ones.<br><br> All of them have chances near this values:<br>bountiful: 80%, 70%, 40%<br>rich: 60%, 50%, 20% <br>medium: 50%, 40%<br>poor: 40%<br><br>Types of gems/ores:<br>hematite - corundum<br>malachite - malachite<br>bismuthinite - lapislazuli<br>cassiterite - olivine<br>sphalerite - fluorite<br>nativesilver - quartz<br>nativegold - quartz<br>limonite - uranium<br>ilmenite - diamond/emerald<br>nativecopper - ruby<br>magnetite - citrine<br>uranium - uranium<br>galena - amethyst<br>",

